node.text:
In March, @AirbnbExperiences hosts all over the world had to stop doing what they love—sharing their interests and passions with others. 
Over the past few weeks, they’ve offered ideas for how to continue hosting even while we’re apart. 
They’ve adapted recipes based on what’s in their pantries, turned living rooms into yoga studios, and choreographed dances for families at home.

Today we’re excited to announce that Airbnb Experiences are now online. You can take a flamenco class with Lidón in Madrid, participate in a tarot card reading with Mak in Austin, or visit a colony of penguins in Cape Town—all from home.

True to Airbnb Experiences in real life, Online Experiences are hosted by remarkable people and set in small groups. Alongside making a new dish, maybe you’ll make a new friend, too.

Thank you to our incredible hosts around the world. We’ll see you online soon —> link in bio.

node.text:
This cave house is not only steps away from Amoudi Bay, but also (more) steps up the stone stairway to the center of Oia. You might find yourself spending more time at sea level, though—a swimming cove and sailboat departure points are a short walk away.

Link in bio for sea breezes away from the crowds.

Photo: @nicolettahouses

Deep in the Hundred Acre Wood, there was a house fit for a bear. In honor of @pooh’s 95th anniversary, Disney appointed illustrator (and your Host) Kim Raymond curated a house sweet enough for Winnie the Pooh. Explore A.A. Milne’s wholesome world by snacking on hunny-infused meals, playing games of Poohsticks and exploring Ashdown Forest, the area that inspired the books 95 years ago.

UK residents can request to book this beary sweet stay on September 20 at 2pm BST. Link in bio.

node.text:
Superhosts Rich and Shannon lovingly restored this 1880s house on the edge of old town. When you feel like wandering, start with a strong local roast from Square One. To stick with the historical theme at night, book a lane at Decades, the vintage bowling alley and arcade just around the corner. 

Link in bio for Pennsylvania Dutch Country home base.

Photo: @thesarahbhoffman

node.text:
Whether you watch from the dome, cabin, hot tub, or hammock, the sunrises and sunsets are the stars of the show at this high-desert retreat. But don’t sleep on the literal stars. “It’s like you could reach out,” says a recent guest, “and pick them out of the sky.”

Link in bio for Superhosts David and Manny’s hideout.

Video: @theorganicretreat

node.accessibility_caption: A wooden room with two caramel-colored sitting chairs and a coffee table in between. The one on the left has a blue throw blanket.

node.text:
Wake to mooing cows at Superhost Andy’s two-story treehouse, which hugs the trunk of an old oak in a horse pasture. When you feel like branching out, head to nearby Ruurlo Castle, a medieval estate that now houses a lively art museum.

Link in bio to sway where you stay.

Photos: @mooieplaatjesbyrt

node.accessibility_caption: A wooden room with two caramel-colored sitting chairs and a coffee table in between. The one on the left has a blue throw blanket.
A wooden treehouse with orange trim sits cocooned around an oak tree.
The bedroom inside the treehouse with caramel colored bedding and throw pillows. There is a nightstand on the right side with blue towels on top and a lamp.
The ceiling of the treehouse is adorned with plants, beams, and hanging light bulbs.
A hammock hangs inside the treehouse with a large branch exposed and a telescope points out the window.
The first floor kitchenette dining counter looks out to a green grassy yard. There are two barstools and two blue plates with two glasses of orange juice.
Photo by Airbnb in Fairfax, California. May be an image of outdoors and tree.

node.text:
Superhost MaryBeth made her tiny house a revitalizing solo sanctuary. Guests love how alive with nature it feels—one noted “hummingbirds coming so close I could feel the vibration of their wings.” Just don’t get so blissed out that you forget to walk into town for a vanilla honey lavender cone from Fairfax Scoop. 

Link in bio for Marin refuge.

Photo: @coleypagan

node.text:
Find peace among the pines at Superhost Dominique’s elegant retreat. After breakfast on your balcony, explore the cobblestone-lined town (Dominique has plenty of local tips) or set sail on Lake Avándaro. 

Link in bio for forest suite.

Photos: @andieac

node.text:
Guests praise every detail of Superhost Susan’s luxury treehouse, from the tilework to the vintage jukebox (bowl of quarters included). They also love her local recommendations, like Mauricio’s for Italian classics and Ralph’s for fresh donuts and apple fritters.

Link in bio for Upper Cumberland home base.

Photo: @sulfurridge

node.text:
Disappear into the jungle at Superhost Mikheyla’s secluded treehouse. If you can ever break the cycle of soaking in your hot tub and plunging into the cool river that runs right under your balcony, climb Mount Manunggal for a broader view of this lush island. 

Link in bio for Cebu sanctuary.

Photos: @mikheylafox

node.text:
Superhost Joan’s house on the Bay of Pollença puts you a short walk from several beaches and the historic walled town. In the unlikely event that it doesn’t satisfy your appetite for majestic views, take the winding drive up to the clifftop Cap de Formentor lighthouse. 

Link in bio for Mallorca magic.

Photo: @wander_lozz

This bamboo villa might just make you rethink the whole indoor bathing fad. It’s surrounded by rice fields but only a five-minute bike ride from the heart of town, where you can start your afternoon with tea by the lotus pond just outside the Saraswati temple.

node.accessibility_caption: A bedroom in neutral tones, with wood beamed ceilings, a hammock in the right corner, next to a wooden door. Besides the door is a wooden chest of four drawers and a floor mirror with the bed with a white comforter and great blanket to the left of the photo.
